WRITING.TITLE: Free college is Racist

WRITING.TEXT: The internet has changed my life in many ways and, considering I was born in 1995, it played a huge role in my life and the juxtaposition of finding out who I am with an excessive influx of influence coming from all directions. I will only post two for the sake of your eyeballs. 1. My freshman year of college I was a criminal justice major, dead set on working in law enforcement with a hope of someday making it to the DEA. I went to school in NH where you get put in a holding cell for having a pipe with marijuana residue in it. I was a normal kid and did drugs in moderation, which i realize sounds kind of hypocritical. My experimental phase of drugs was a result of the internet and the wide open window it provided for unfiltered, useful knowledge and shared experiences. I learned more about the useless war on drugs from the internet than I ever did in any classroom. This, paired with the CJ program advisor telling me that any job in the field would require a polygraph inquiring about my drug use in the past 5 years, funneled me into a more fitting career path. 2. While I was growing up, nobody got famous from being funny or entertaining on the internet. It wasn't nearly as accessible or widely utilized as it has been as of late. It's been a very quick leap from being forced off the dial-up internet by my mother so she could make a phone call to literally being able to stream Pay Per View events on my cell phone. Making videos and drawing in laughs and views from all over the world, while making a living, has never been something that I was raised to think as "possible". Yet, it is something that I am currently trying to do. There is a popular comedy/sports website that I have been in touch with over the past few months and one of the employees recently asked me to make a video for them. I have zero experience in videography, however comedy is something I have a great passion for. I recently gathered two other kids that I have met once or twice and started to make a plan for a video I wanted to do. They are videography weapons and I enjoy being on camera so it was one of those "meeting of the minds" ideas. The premise that was requested by the company was simple and stupid (interviewing drunk college kids); however, I finally had someone who wanted to see what I could do. We absolutely nailed the video and it is currently being edited (hopefully being finalized in a week or two). The point being is that the internet opened HUGE doors for me. Being "creative" was only a thing for music, drama, and art kids growing up and I was never really "socially allowed" to show that side of myself. It was a side of me that has been aching to come out ever since I was a kid. The internet showed me that not only is it okay to be openly creative and take risks with creative ideas, but it allowed me to give it a shot. I really hope it works out because this is something that is so new, so possible, and so revolutionary. Sorry for all the words - I told you, it was for the sake of your eyeballs.
